      "latency_ms": 2261.2,
      "prompt_tokens": 11,
      "completion_tokens": 508,
      "output": "At its most fundamental level, **water** is a chemical compound made up of two elements: **hydrogen** and **oxygen**. Its chemical formula is **$H_2O$**, meaning every single molecule of water consists of two hydrogen atoms bonded to one oxygen atom. \n\nHowever, water is much more than just a chemical formula. It is one of the most abundant, unique, and essential substances in the universe. Here is a breakdown of what water is through different lenses:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Physical and Chemical Properties\nWater is famous for having several \"weird\" scientific properties that defy normal rules of chemistry, making it uniquely suited to support life:\n\n* **The Three States:** Water is the only natural substance on Earth that exists abundantly in three physical states: **liquid** (water), **solid** (ice), and **gas** (vapor/steam).\n* **The Universal Solvent:** Because of its chemical structure (it is a \"polar\" molecule, meaning the oxygen side has a slight negative charge and the hydrogen side has a slight positive charge), water can dissolve more substances than any other liquid. This is why it carries nutrients through our bloodstreams and minerals through the soil.\n* **Ice Floats:** Almost all substances shrink and become denser when they freeze. Water, however, *expands* and becomes less dense when it turns to ice. This is why ice floats on lakes, creating an insulating layer that allows aquatic life to survive underneath during winter.\n* **High Heat Capacity:** Water can absorb a lot of heat before its temperature changes significantly. This helps regulate the climate of the entire planet and keeps living organisms from overheating.\n\n### 2. Ecological Importance (Earth's Lifeblood)\nWater is often called the \"cradle of life.\" \n* **Global Coverage:** About **71% of Earth's surface** is covered in water, mostly by oceans (which hold about 96.5% of all Earth's water). \n* **The Water Cycle:** Water is constantly recycled through the Earth in a closed system known as the hydrologic cycle. It evaporates from oceans and lakes, forms clouds, falls as rain or snow (precipitation), and flows back into bodies of water.\n* **Habitats:** Oceans, rivers, and lakes provide homes for millions of species of plants and animals.\n\n### 3. Biological Importance (The Essence of Life)\nLife as we know it cannot exist without water."
